GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 2
SENATE BILL 579
Education/Higher Education Committee Substitute Adopted 4/30/25
Short Title: Transforming the High School Experience. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
March 26, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ESTABLISH THE NORTH CAROLINA HIGH SCHOOL REDESIGN
3 COMMISSION, TO ESTABLISH VARIOUS COMPETENCY-BASED LEARNING
4 PROGRAMS, AND TO PROVIDE LEGISLATIVE INTENT AS TO AMOUNTS AND
5 USES OF APPROPRIATIONS FOR THESE PURPOSES.
6 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
7
8 PART I. NORTH CAROLINA HIGH SCHOOL REDESIGN COMMISSION
9 SECTION 1.(a) Commission Established. – There is established the North Carolina
10 High School Redesign Commission (Commission). The Commission shall be located
11 administratively in the Department of Public Instruction but shall exercise all of its prescribed
12 powers independently of the Department. The purpose of the Commission is to explore and
13 recommend changes to policies and systems governing high school and higher education that
14 will better prepare North Carolina students for success as they transition to higher education or
15 the workforce.
16 SECTION 1.(b) Commission Membership. – The Commission shall consist of 15
17 members as follows:
18 (1) Two members appointed by the General Assembly upon recommendation of
19 the Speaker of the House of Representatives.
20 (2) Two members appointed by the General Assembly upon recommendation of
21 the President Pro Tempore of the Senate.
22 (3) One member appointed by the Governor.
23 (4) The State Superintendent of Public Instruction or his or her designee.
24 (5) The President of The University of North Carolina or his or her designee.
25 (6) The President of North Carolina Independent Colleges and Universities or his
26 or her designee.
27 (7) The President of the North Carolina Community College System or his or her
28 designee.
29 (8) The chief executive officers of each of the following organizations, or their
30 designees: MyFutureNC, the North Carolina Chamber of Commerce, BEST
31 NC, and SparkNC.
32 (9) One chief administrative officer or president of a community college
33 participating in a program, project, or initiative developed pursuant to this act
34 and one superintendent of a local school administrative unit participating in a
35 program, project, or initiative developed pursuant to this act or their respective
*S579-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 designees. These members shall be appointed by the chair of the Commission
2 elected pursuant to subsection (c) of this section.
3 SECTION 1.(c) The Commission shall elect a chair from the members appointed by
4 the General Assembly. Each member shall have one vote for the chair, except those members to
5 be appointed by the chair pursuant to subdivision (9) of subsection (b) of this section who shall
6 be appointed after a chair is elected. The Commission shall meet at least four times annually. The
7 Commission shall meet on the call of the chair or as additionally provided by the Commission.
8 A quorum is six members of the Commission. Members may not vote by proxy.
9 SECTION 1.(d) All members shall be appointed to terms for the entire duration of
10 the Commission. Any vacancy in a term shall be filled by the appointing authority for the
11 remainder of the unexpired term.
12 SECTION 1.(e) Commission Duties. – The Commission shall examine promising
13 practices in North Carolina and nationally to inform the Commission's recommendations. At a
14 minimum, the Commission shall consider the following:
15 (1) Flexible requirements for high school diplomas that are relevant to the
16 knowledge, skills, and abilities students will need for success in the future
17 workforce.
18 (2) Access to apprenticeships, internships, clinical experiences, and other
19 high-quality, work-based learning experiences while in high school.
20 (3) Opportunities for students to earn industry recognized credentials while in
21 high school.
22 (4) Partnerships between public school units and North Carolina Community
23 Colleges, The University of North Carolina, and North Carolina Independent
24 Colleges and Universities for the purposes of facilitating subdivisions (1)
25 through (3) of this subsection.
26 (5) Personalized pathways for students to satisfy core graduation requirements.
27 (6) Modular credit bearing alternatives to semester or yearlong courses.
28 (7) Competency-based alternatives to time bound courses.
29 (8) Strategies for extending learning beyond school walls at scale via community
30 connected experiences, including incorporating incentives for local businesses
31 to partner with schools.
32 (9) Uses of artificial intelligence to expand student opportunities to engage in
33 career exploration and work-based learning experiences.
34 (10) Alternative funding models to enable the development of a statewide learning
35 ecosystem that encourages subdivisions (1) through (9) of this subsection.
36 (11) Career exploration opportunities for students in middle school and the first
37 two years of high school that prepare students to engage successfully in a
38 redesigned high school experience.
39 (12) Evaluation of the programs, projects, and initiatives established by this act,
40 and any other competency-based education (CBE) programs or high school
41 redesign efforts taking place in the State. The Commission shall partner with
42 the Office of Learning Research at the North Carolina Collaboratory to
43 conduct these evaluations.
44 SECTION 1.(f) Meetings and Organization. – The chair shall designate one or more
45 of the organizations identified in subdivision (8) of Section 1(b) of this act to plan and manage
46 Commission meetings and draft reports. Designated organizations shall provide administrative
47 staff for meetings. Funds appropriated to the Department of Public Instruction to be used to
48 contract with one or more organizations to plan and manage Commission meetings shall be
49 divided equally among the organizations designated by the chair unless otherwise agreed by the
50 chair and all designated organizations.
Page 2 Senate Bill 579-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 1.(g) Report. – The Commission shall submit a report to the Joint
2 Legislative Education Oversight Committee by April 30, 2026, and annually thereafter. The
3 reports shall include all recommendations approved by a majority of Commission members and
4 a summary of any evaluations of the efficacy of any CBE programs and high school redesign
5 efforts implemented during the current school year.
6 SECTION 1.(h) The Commission shall terminate on June 30, 2030, or upon filing
7 of its final annual report, whichever occurs first.
8
9 PART II. COMPETENCY-BASED HIGH SCHOOL AND HEALTHCARE AND
10 HIGH-TECH PATHWAYS PROGRAM
11 SECTION 2.(a) Program Established; Purpose. – There is established the
12 Competency-Based High School and Healthcare and High-Tech Pathways Program (Program).
13 The purpose of the Program is to create pathways that will utilize competency-based education
14 (CBE). Pathways will result in obtaining either an associate degree or an industry recognized
15 credential/certification/licensure based on the student's goal of employment or enrollment.
16 Students will decide their college or career track at the end of their junior year with an initial
17 emphasis on healthcare preparation.
18 SECTION 2.(b) Participants. – Mooresville Graded School District (MGSD) shall
19 partner with Mitchell Community College (MCC) to implement the Program.
20 SECTION 2.(c) Program Time Line. – MGSD, in collaboration with MCC, shall
21 contract with an organization with demonstrated expertise in designing and implementing
22 learner-centered, modular, and competency-based high school programs that align with emerging
23 healthcare and high-tech career pathways. The organization shall have experience in
24 co-designing stackable credentials with public school units and higher education partners and a
25 documented track record of developing digital infrastructure that supports student-paced
26 progression, interdisciplinary learning, and real-world skill acquisition. This organization shall
27 assist in developing a framework for the Program, including course design, sequencing,
28 credentialing structure, and other elements necessary for personalized student progression during
29 the 2025-2026 school year. Students will have the opportunity to participate in a pathway
30 provided by the Program by the 2027-2028 school year at the latest.
31 SECTION 2.(d) Program Flexibilities. – Notwithstanding any provision of law to
32 the contrary, the following flexibilities shall be available to Program participants:
33 (1) MGSD may offer Credit by Demonstrated Mastery assessments and CTE
34 Proof of Learning assessments outside of existing State testing windows.
35 (2) MCC may enroll MGSD students in community college courses prior to their
36 eleventh grade year without the student meeting the requirements for ninth
37 and tenth grade students pursuant to subdivision (4) of G.S. 115D-20.
38 (3) Students participating in the Program shall have access to all community
39 college courses at MCC, regardless of pathway selection.
40 (4) MGSD may replace any high school graduation credit requirement, except
41 those outlined in this subdivision, with either community college courses
42 offered by MCC or locally developed CBE courses that are consistent with
43 the student's pathway. MGSD shall not replace any graduation credit
44 requirements in the following subject areas:
45 a. English.
46 b. Mathematics.
47 c. Science.
48 d. Social Studies.
49 (5) MGSD may operate any high school in the local school administrative unit
50 consistent with the flexibilities of a school operating under a restart model
51 pursuant to G.S. 115C-105.37B(a)(2).
Senate Bill 579-Second Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 2.(e) Selection of Third-Party Vendor. – MGSD shall select a third-party
2 vendor (Vendor) that is an educational support provider with a nationally recognized,
3 research-based instructional and leadership framework, including a High Reliability School
4 model, a taxonomy of educational objectives aligned to classroom strategies, and a system for
5 implementing personalized competency-based education. The Vendor shall have published
6 extensively in peer-reviewed and practitioner literature, have an established track record of
7 working directly with K-12 schools and districts across multiple states, and offer professional
8 development services, implementation support, and instructional resources developed and led by
9 a founding education researcher with over four decades of influence in curriculum, instruction,
10 and assessment.
11 SECTION 2.(f) MGSD Partnership with Vendor. – MGSD shall partner with the
12 Vendor selected pursuant to subsection (e) of this section to develop standards-aligned
13 proficiency scales for all content areas in grades nine through 12 to ensure educators in the
14 participating schools have the tools necessary to successfully transition to CBE approaches. The
15 Vendor shall provide professional development and coaching to the schools in MGSD to ensure
16 educators can engage in learning about CBE approaches, including implementation of the
17 proficiency scales developed by MGSD.
18 SECTION 2.(g) Funding. – It is the intention of the General Assembly to appropriate
19 from the General Fund to the Department of Public Instruction the sum of up to two million
20 dollars ($2,000,000) in nonrecurring funds for each year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium. These
21 funds would not revert but remain available until the end of the 2026-2027 fiscal year. These
22 funds would be allocated to MGSD for the following purposes:
23 (1) To contract with experts in CBE and designing stackable credentials pursuant
24 to subsection (c) of this section.
25 (2) To hire one additional staff member at MGSD to oversee implementation of
26 the Program.
27 (3) To partner with a Vendor pursuant to subsection (f) of this section.
28
29 PART III. LIGHTHOUSE MATH PROJECT
30 SECTION 3.(a) Project Established; Purpose. – There is established the Lighthouse
31 Math Project (Project). The purpose of the Project is to increase the percentage of high school
32 students who are (i) eligible to complete college level mathematics upon graduation from high
33 school and (ii) able to complete college level math either through dual enrollment while in high
34 school or within the first year of college enrollment.
35 SECTION 3.(b) Project Participants. – Wake Technical Community College (Wake
36 Tech) shall partner with Wake County Public School System (WCPSS) for high school students
37 at East Wake High School and Knightdale High School to be eligible to participate in the Project
38 at the Wake Tech East campus of Wake Tech. Wake Tech and WCPSS shall partner with
39 SparkNC to align the Project participants' ongoing efforts at the Wake Tech East campus with
40 the design and implementation of the Project.
41 SECTION 3.(c) Project Commitments. – WCPSS, in collaboration with Wake Tech,
42 shall contract with Khan Academy, Inc. (Khan), for use of the artificial intelligence student
43 tutoring program, Khanmigo. Students enrolling at participating high schools shall have access
44 to Khanmigo from the time of enrollment in the high school and continuing through their
45 attendance at Wake Tech if the student chooses to enroll at Wake Tech East. Wake Tech shall
46 collaborate with Khan to do the following:
47 (1) Develop and deliver at least one Khanmigo-centered gateway college math
48 course to be offered to high school students at participating high schools to be
49 completed as a college level math course. This course shall also be available
50 to students who graduate from participating high schools and enroll in the
51 courses at Wake Tech East.
Page 4 Senate Bill 579-Second Edition

