1 (2) Develop a Khanmigo-centered developmental math course sequence that will
2 be provided by Wake Tech faculty to students from participating high schools
3 in one of the following formats:
4 a. As part of a Career and College Promise Career Ready Pathway.
5 b. As supplement to a Career and College Promise Pathway.
6 c. As a summer bridge program available to students prior to or
7 subsequent to their junior and senior years of high school.
8 d. As a community college course during the first semester of enrollment
9 at Wake Tech.
10 SECTION 3.(d) Modular Math Course – As part of the Project, Khan, in consultation
11 with Wake Tech and WCPSS, shall work to develop a self-paced, competency-based modular
12 math course with appropriate student diagnostics and student assessments based on the college
13 readiness math competencies provided as part of the Project. It is the intent that students
14 successfully demonstrating college readiness math competencies will be eligible to enroll in
15 college level math courses.
16 SECTION 3.(e) Funding; DPI. – It is the intention of the General Assembly to
17 appropriate from the General Fund to the Department of Public Instruction the sum of up to five
18 hundred thousand dollars ($500,000) in nonrecurring funds for the 2025-2026 fiscal year to
19 contract with Khan for licenses for the Khanmigo application and to create the course developed
20 pursuant to subdivision (1) of subsection (c) of this section. It is the intention of the General
21 Assembly that funds appropriated for the purposes laid out in this section shall not revert but
22 shall remain available to accomplish the purposes of this section until the end of the 2026-2027
23 fiscal year.
24 SECTION 3.(f) Funding; NCCCS. – It is the intention of the General Assembly to
25 appropriate from the General Fund to the Community Colleges System Office the sum of up to
26 one million dollars ($1,000,000) in nonrecurring funds for the 2025-2026 fiscal year to be used
27 to establish time-limited positions at Wake Tech. Two positions shall be assigned to work in each
28 participating high school to assist in the implementation of the courses offered by the Project. It
29 is the intention of the General Assembly that funds appropriated for the purposes laid out in this
30 section shall not revert but shall remain available to accomplish the purposes of this section until
31 the end of the 2028-2029 fiscal year.
32
33 PART IV. COMMUNITY COLLEGE SEAMLESS SKILLS INITIATIVE
34 SECTION 4.(a) Initiative Established; Purpose. – There is established the
35 Community College Seamless Skills Initiative (Initiative). The purpose of the Initiative is to
36 create a competency-based education (CBE) model that seamlessly connects high school and
37 community college. By aligning learning experiences from high school with college-level
38 competencies, the Initiative shall enable students to explore career pathways, earn dual credit,
39 and fulfill computer science requirements while gaining credentials of value in high-demand
40 technology employment sectors through college credit.
41 SECTION 4.(b) Initiative Participants. – Fayetteville Technical Community College
42 (FTCC) and Wilkes Community College (WCC) shall partner to implement the duties of the
43 Initiative.
44 SECTION 4.(c) Initiative Commitments. – The Initiative shall commit to
45 accomplishing each of the following:
46 (1) Establish high-tech pathways that will integrate high school and community
47 college curricula for hands-on, project-based learning.
48 (2) Develop competency-based pathways that will create cross-curricular maps
49 for dual credit, fostering seamless transitions between secondary and
50 postsecondary education.
Senate Bill 579-Second Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) Scale and replicate to be able to build a scalable framework for rapid
2 implementation across North Carolina.
3 (4) Empower student ownership by enabling students to set long-term learning
4 goals and to manage and own their credentials with a digital wallet.
5 (5) Facilitate student work experiences to accelerate learning and transition
6 students into work through "learn & earn" work-based learning in partnership
7 with public agencies and private employers.
8 (6) Address workforce needs by developing and sustaining a comprehensive
9 talent pipeline of skilled workers for high-demand technology fields in
10 occupations that depend upon informational technology and operational
11 technology for operational success.
12 (7) Develop statewide resources, including a guidebook to facilitate model
13 replication and a new talent development model to accelerate learning using
14 CBE.
15 SECTION 4.(d) Digital Wallet. – The participants in the Initiative shall contract
16 with a third-party entity to create a secure, interoperable digital wallet platform capable of
17 issuing, storing, verifying, and sharing learner credentials, including microcredentials,
18 certifications, transcripts, and verified skill records. The platform shall allow for credential
19 portability across educational institutions and employers, support open standards for
20 interoperability, and ensure privacy and security in compliance with applicable laws. The
21 platform shall enable learners to manage a comprehensive, lifelong record of achievement that is
22 accessible, verifiable, and shareable with third parties through digital means. All credential and
23 learner data shall be owned and controlled by the student and shall not be stored in centralized
24 cloud infrastructure.
25 SECTION 4.(e) Support. – The North Carolina Community Colleges System Office
26 shall provide ongoing technical support to community colleges participating in the Initiative.
27 FTCC shall enter into a memorandum of understanding with WCC to jointly co-design the
28 Initiative. As part of this effort, the colleges shall engage an organization with demonstrated
29 expertise in designing and implementing learner-centered, modular, and competency-based high
30 school programs aligned with emerging and high-tech career pathways. The selected
31 organization shall have a history of co-designing stackable credentials with public school units
32 and postsecondary institutions and a proven track record of building digital infrastructure that
33 supports student-paced progression, interdisciplinary instruction, and authentic skill
34 development. The organization shall assist in the development of a comprehensive framework
35 for the Initiative, including course design, sequencing, credentialing structure, and related
36 elements necessary to support personalized student progression during the 2025-2026 school
37 year.
38 SECTION 4.(f) Funding. – It is the intention of the General Assembly to appropriate
39 from the General Fund to the North Carolina Community Colleges System Office the sum of up
40 to three million seven hundred fifty thousand dollars ($3,750,000) in nonrecurring funds for the
41 2025-2026 fiscal year to be allocated to FTCC and WCC for the purposes outlined in this section.
42 To the extent funds are appropriated for this purpose, the sum of up to two million seven hundred
43 fifty thousand dollars ($2,750,000) shall be allocated to FTCC and the sum of up to one million
44 dollars ($1,000,000) shall be allocated to WCC. Funds allocated for the purposes outlined in this
45 section shall not revert but shall remain available until the end of the 2028-2029 fiscal year.
46
47 PART V. COMPETENCY-BASED EDUCATION AND HIGH SCHOOL REDESIGN
48 STRATEGIC NETWORK
49 SECTION 5. Mooresville Graded School District, Mitchell Community College,
50 Wake Technical Community College, Wake County Public School System, Fayetteville
51 Technical Community College, Wilkes Community College, and SparkNC shall collaborate to
Page 6 Senate Bill 579-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 create a Competency-Based Education and High School Redesign Strategic Network (Network).
2 The president of SparkNC, or the president's designee, shall serve as the chair of the Network.
3 The chair shall coordinate the operations of the Network and provide administrative and technical
4 support for the Network to the extent such support is necessary. The Network shall provide a
5 means for each entity to share what it has learned and developed regarding CBE and high school
6 redesign. The goals of the Network shall be to advance the goals of developing a CBE approach
7 to education across the State.
8
9 PART VI. OFFICE OF LEARNING RESEARCH EVALUATION
10 SECTION 6.(a) Study and Evaluation. – The Office of Learning Research at the
11 North Carolina Collaboratory shall study and evaluate the programs and initiatives established
12 pursuant to Sections 2, 3, 4, and 5 of this act and report to the Joint Legislative Education
13 Oversight Committee by March 15, 2027, and annually thereafter, culminating in a final report
14 on March 15, 2030. Reports shall include at least the following:
15 (1) The total number of students engaging with these programs.
16 (2) The total amount of funds expended to implement, design, and operate the
17 programs.
18 (3) Effects on student achievement and learning outcomes.
19 SECTION 6.(b) Funding. – It is the intention of the General Assembly to appropriate
20 from the General Fund to the Board of Governors of The University of North Carolina the sum
21 of up to four hundred fifty thousand dollars ($450,000) in nonrecurring funds for the 2025-2026
22 fiscal year to be allocated to the North Carolina Collaboratory for the Office of Learning
23 Research to conduct the study and evaluation required by this section.
24
25 PART VII. EFFECTIVE DATE
26 SECTION 7. This act becomes effective when the Current Operations
27 Appropriations Act of 2025 becomes law and if that bill appropriates funds for the purposes
28 detailed in each section of this act.
